00:38:18.690 --> 00:38:20.340
Those incorporate into a story.

00:38:20.340 --> 00:38:22.280
You've had this since
the Roger Corman days.

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:24.390
You want your prison
film with the girl fight,

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:25.770
with the guns and everything.

00:38:25.770 --> 00:38:27.610
And you make whatever you want--

00:38:27.610 --> 00:38:29.050
MICHAEL SMITH: Speak for
yourself, but go ahead.

00:38:29.050 --> 00:38:29.675
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:38:29.675 --> 00:38:30.470
You have that.

00:38:30.470 --> 00:38:32.630
Even there's a book
from a couple years ago

00:38:32.630 --> 00:38:35.740
that was talking about
scripts for big budget films,

00:38:35.740 --> 00:38:39.380
"The Dark Knight" and the
second Star Trek movie

00:38:39.380 --> 00:38:40.900
were made from the same thing.

00:38:40.900 --> 00:38:43.334
One had a good execution,
one not so good.

00:38:43.334 --> 00:38:44.500
People didn't respond to it.

00:38:44.500 --> 00:38:47.520
They do the same plot points
at the same beats in the movie.

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:50.530
If you time them,
they're roughly a bad guy

00:38:50.530 --> 00:38:52.795
gets captured, bad
guy gets let go.

00:38:52.795 --> 00:38:54.920
They're doing these things
at the exact same times,

00:38:54.920 --> 00:38:58.090
except one does it well,
one doesn't do it so well.

00:38:58.090 --> 00:39:00.417
So there is artistry to allow
for with the data points.

00:39:00.417 --> 00:39:01.500
MICHAEL SMITH: No, no, no.

00:39:01.500 --> 00:39:04.710
And again, we're not claiming
that the artistry goes away.

00:39:04.710 --> 00:39:07.770
I think all we're claiming
is that you can do things

00:39:07.770 --> 00:39:12.140
profitably in an on-demand
platform that wouldn't be

00:39:12.140 --> 00:39:15.440
profitable in a la carte sales.

00:39:15.440 --> 00:39:16.490
But go ahead.

00:39:16.490 --> 00:39:18.200
AUDIENCE: Sure, but
along those lines,

00:39:18.200 --> 00:39:20.170
are you also
considering the fact

00:39:20.170 --> 00:39:23.484
that for the television
environment, the theater

00:39:23.484 --> 00:39:24.900
environment you
have to allot time

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:30.144
for the next showing, the
commercials, the trailers.

00:39:30.144 --> 00:39:31.560
Online, you don't
have to do that.

00:39:31.560 --> 00:39:34.430
So it's also allowing
for a longer time

00:39:34.430 --> 00:39:37.260
to tell a story can
make those better

00:39:37.260 --> 00:39:39.610
stories even more better.

00:39:39.610 --> 00:39:42.330
But the garbage shows,
they kind of just

00:39:42.330 --> 00:39:45.195
stick around a
little bit longer.

00:39:45.195 --> 00:39:47.320
MICHAEL SMITH: Again, I
would go back to the notion

00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:48.360
that-- you are absolutely right.

00:39:48.360 --> 00:39:50.119
In a world where I
don't have commercials,

00:39:50.119 --> 00:39:51.660
in a world where I
don't have to wait

00:39:51.660 --> 00:39:54.830
a week to see the next
episode, I can do stuff.

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:58.250
I can make stuff work that
wouldn't work in broadcast.

00:39:58.250 --> 00:40:01.860
To me, "Arrested Development"
is the classic example of this.

00:40:01.860 --> 00:40:04.810
If you fell into
"Arrested Development"

00:40:04.810 --> 00:40:08.650
season 3, episode 5, you would
have no idea what's going on.

00:40:08.650 --> 00:40:12.750
The show only makes sense if you
can go back and get caught up.

00:40:12.750 --> 00:40:15.720
"Stranger Things"
is another example.

00:40:15.720 --> 00:40:19.050
It makes sense because
you can binge it.

00:40:19.050 --> 00:40:21.440
So it's not, in a
sense, that Hollywood

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:23.620
lost their creative mojo.

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:27.520
It's just that, again, the
new on-demand platforms

00:40:27.520 --> 00:40:29.870
allow you to do stuff
that you just couldn't do

00:40:29.870 --> 00:40:32.330
in a traditional broadcast way.

00:40:32.330 --> 00:40:35.710
But execution, creativity is
absolutely still important.

00:40:35.710 --> 00:40:37.040
There's no doubt about that.

00:40:37.040 --> 00:40:39.840
Did that sort of
answer your question?

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:40.540
MICHAEL SMITH: Do you
want to jump in on this?

00:40:40.540 --> 00:40:41.720
RAHUL TELANG: I'm just
saying just because you

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:43.145
have data doesn't
mean that you'll

00:40:43.145 --> 00:40:45.230
end up making better shows.

00:40:45.230 --> 00:40:48.170
I mean, at some
level, the talent that

00:40:48.170 --> 00:40:50.970
is available to the Netflix
in terms of creative

00:40:50.970 --> 00:40:52.450
is the same talent,
to an extent,

00:40:52.450 --> 00:40:54.670
available to sometimes
the large Hollywood

00:40:54.670 --> 00:40:56.740
studio, except that
maybe Netflix has

00:40:56.740 --> 00:40:59.230
these other advantages,
that is it doesn't have

00:40:59.230 --> 00:41:03.570
to be a linear story from
9:00 to 9:45, take a break,

00:41:03.570 --> 00:41:04.790
then come back.

00:41:04.790 --> 00:41:08.810
Whereas in the Netflix, you
could have 20 hours of show

00:41:08.810 --> 00:41:11.580
in mind versus a
chunk of 45 minutes.

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:14.240
That also probably makes
it more enriching, maybe,

00:41:14.240 --> 00:41:17.900
to the creator if you
have, again, people who

00:41:17.900 --> 00:41:18.980
can make good stories.

00:41:18.980 --> 00:41:20.975
Of course, I mean, if
you have poor execution,

00:41:20.975 --> 00:41:22.760
it doesn't matter what you have.

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:26.436
So, as I said, in baseball, if
you have access to good data,

00:41:26.436 --> 00:41:28.560
it doesn't mean that you
can make a better picture.

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:30.250
The picture is still going
to be the same picture.

00:41:30.250 --> 00:41:31.750
But if you have
access to good data,

00:41:31.750 --> 00:41:33.640
maybe you can
identify the talent

00:41:33.640 --> 00:41:36.600
and then nurture the talent
and then promote and support

00:41:36.600 --> 00:41:38.587
that talent, I think.

00:41:38.587 --> 00:41:40.420
MICHAEL SMITH: Maybe
another way to describe

00:41:40.420 --> 00:41:43.710
this is, why did
Netflix sign Adam

00:41:43.710 --> 00:41:46.840
Sandler to a five-movie deal?

00:41:46.840 --> 00:41:49.500
And why did Amazon
sign Woody Allen

00:41:49.500 --> 00:41:51.800
to write a television show?

00:41:51.800 --> 00:41:54.510
I think you could make an
argument that both Adam Sandler

00:41:54.510 --> 00:41:58.580
and Woody Allen are niche
tastes, acquired tastes.

00:41:58.580 --> 00:42:02.260
So why might they work
for Netflix and Amazon

00:42:02.260 --> 00:42:04.350
not for anybody in the
traditional industry?

00:42:04.350 --> 00:42:06.900
Because Netflix and Amazon know
exactly who the Woody Allen

00:42:06.900 --> 00:42:09.800
fans are and exactly-- I'll
point at Hal-- exactly who

00:42:09.800 --> 00:42:14.040
the Adam Sandler fans are.

00:42:14.040 --> 00:42:16.590
And they can promote
that content to them

00:42:16.590 --> 00:42:17.790
much more efficiently.

00:42:17.790 --> 00:42:19.990
And at least by all
public announcements,

00:42:19.990 --> 00:42:23.570
Netflix is arguing that its
Adam Sandler creations have been

00:42:23.570 --> 00:42:24.864
a huge hit for the platform.

00:42:24.864 --> 00:42:26.530
AUDIENCE: So, I guess,
what do you think

00:42:26.530 --> 00:42:30.080
about the recommendation
systems and the black hole

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:32.330
sort of thing, where I
discover you like peanut butter

00:42:32.330 --> 00:42:33.746
and jelly sandwiches,
so I'm going

00:42:33.746 --> 00:42:36.190
to give you all these variants
of peanut butter and jelly.

00:42:36.190 --> 00:42:38.106
You don't like peanut
butter and jelly anymore

00:42:38.106 --> 00:42:41.260
because I inundated you with
peanut butter and jelly.

00:42:41.260 --> 00:42:44.280
What do you think is the danger
there with data-based story

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:44.780
telling?

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:46.655
RAHUL TELANG: So I'll
give one quick example.

00:42:46.655 --> 00:42:48.880
I was reading--
actually, a reporter

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:51.020
was asking me about it,
so it came to my mind.

00:42:51.020 --> 00:42:54.287
So apparently Spotify runs--
I am not a Spotify subscriber,

00:42:54.287 --> 00:42:56.120
so I don't know all the
details, but Spotify

00:42:56.120 --> 00:42:58.277
has this-- what-- Discover
Playlist or something?

00:42:58.277 --> 00:42:59.110
MICHAEL SMITH: Yeah.

00:42:59.110 --> 00:43:01.480
RAHUL TELANG: So, apparently,
this Discover Playlist

00:43:01.480 --> 00:43:03.690
on Spotify is widely popular.

00:43:03.690 --> 00:43:05.149
People love the
Discover Playlist.

00:43:05.149 --> 00:43:07.190
And I was actually reading
a little bit about it.

00:43:07.190 --> 00:43:11.560
What it is-- and it was nothing
but a recommendation system

00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:14.090
to figure out what
songs people love.

00:43:14.090 --> 00:43:17.450
And this, to my-- I guess
I shouldn't be surprised,

00:43:17.450 --> 00:43:19.870
I'm from Carnegie Mellon--
the recommendation system is

00:43:19.870 --> 00:43:21.770
basically built on
this deep machine

00:43:21.770 --> 00:43:24.650
learning, the deep learning
theory of machine learning.

00:43:24.650 --> 00:43:29.270
And I said, could it offer
you a bad recommendation?

00:43:29.270 --> 00:43:31.410
Of course, it could offer
you a bad recommendation.

00:43:31.410 --> 00:43:35.950
But it seems like our
data analytics is getting

00:43:35.950 --> 00:43:37.350
more and more sophisticated.

00:43:37.350 --> 00:43:39.740
And new ones that,
more likely than not,

00:43:39.740 --> 00:43:43.030
it is actually going to delight
users rather than disappoint

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:44.190
users.

00:43:44.190 --> 00:43:46.230
Even with our
recommendation engine,

00:43:46.230 --> 00:43:50.170
human recommendations also
have significant amount

00:43:50.170 --> 00:43:52.030
of bad hit rate.

00:43:52.030 --> 00:43:55.310
So at some level, we're
comparing the world

00:43:55.310 --> 00:43:59.580
before the engine versus after
these engines came about.

00:43:59.580 --> 00:44:04.390
And I actually feel that most of
the people are actually happy.

00:44:04.390 --> 00:44:08.050
And they'll get even
better with time

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:12.706
rather than relying on human
curators who are probably as

00:44:12.706 --> 00:44:15.650
crappy as we expect them to be.

00:44:15.650 --> 00:44:17.670
MICHAEL SMITH: Well,
I would actually use--

00:44:17.670 --> 00:44:19.670
and hopefully this won't
be pandering to anybody

00:44:19.670 --> 00:44:21.960
in the audience-- but
my favorite example I

00:44:21.960 --> 00:44:25.090
use in class is just to take a
screenshot of my YouTube front

00:44:25.090 --> 00:44:26.150
page.

00:44:26.150 --> 00:44:28.420
You've got Rolling Stones clips.

00:44:28.420 --> 00:44:30.370
You've got baseball highlights.

00:44:30.370 --> 00:44:32.950
You've got "West
Wing" episode clips.

00:44:32.950 --> 00:44:35.620
I mean, you guys do
an amazingly good job

00:44:35.620 --> 00:44:37.830
of presenting me with
16 different clips

00:44:37.830 --> 00:44:41.751
that I can easily waste 45
minutes on just exploring

00:44:41.751 --> 00:44:42.250
around.

00:44:42.250 --> 00:44:45.580
And I think being
able to say, here

00:44:45.580 --> 00:44:47.076
are a bunch of
recommendations, it

00:44:47.076 --> 00:44:49.200
looks like Mike isn't
clicking on the peanut butter

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:50.870
and jelly ones as
much as he once

00:44:50.870 --> 00:44:54.290
did, let's transition to
something new, I think

00:44:54.290 --> 00:44:56.190
is actually pretty
darn powerful.

00:44:56.190 --> 00:44:59.760
And I think you guys actually do
an amazingly good job at that.

00:44:59.760 --> 00:45:00.710
And thank you.

00:45:00.710 --> 00:45:02.740
AUDIENCE: He's discovered
his Google profile.

00:45:02.740 --> 00:45:02.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:02.890 --> 00:45:04.098
MICHAEL SMITH: Yeah, exactly.

00:45:06.690 --> 00:45:08.017
Question from a former student.

00:45:08.017 --> 00:45:08.600
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:45:08.600 --> 00:45:08.920
MICHAEL SMITH: I hear you.

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:10.570
AUDIENCE: I studied
[INAUDIBLE] so I

00:45:10.570 --> 00:45:14.250
like to ask you a question.

00:45:14.250 --> 00:45:17.070
So it seems like there's
some sort of a war going on,

00:45:17.070 --> 00:45:21.499
like a battle going on between
the incumbent entertainment

00:45:21.499 --> 00:45:23.707
players versus the ones that
are already established.

00:45:26.266 --> 00:45:27.640
Who do you think
is going to win?

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:30.680
Or where do you think
is the stabilization

00:45:30.680 --> 00:45:33.422
point between this?

00:45:33.422 --> 00:45:35.130
MICHAEL SMITH: You
want to take this one?

00:45:35.130 --> 00:45:37.338
RAHUL TELANG: I don't know
if there's a war going on,

00:45:37.338 --> 00:45:40.740
but I would say that the
traditional players are not

00:45:40.740 --> 00:45:46.200
used to an entry from basically
a technology start-up who

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:47.550
used to be just a distributor.

00:45:47.550 --> 00:45:49.450
I mean, it was a
DVD distributor--

00:45:49.450 --> 00:45:51.344
that's what Netflix
was-- and then became

00:45:51.344 --> 00:45:52.510
a distributor for streaming.

00:45:52.510 --> 00:45:56.250
And now it realized
that it can actually

00:45:56.250 --> 00:45:58.600
do a pretty good job
of creating content

00:45:58.600 --> 00:46:04.750
and just make vertically
integrated, all in one shop.

00:46:04.750 --> 00:46:07.820
Now who is going to win?

00:46:07.820 --> 00:46:10.906
The ground fact is that I
think some of the things

00:46:10.906 --> 00:46:12.280
that we mention
in the book, that

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:16.290
is having access to audience,
having this huge customer base,

00:46:16.290 --> 00:46:19.200
having ability to
identify their interests,

00:46:19.200 --> 00:46:22.380
I think they are going to play
an increasingly important role

00:46:22.380 --> 00:46:25.100
in giving you a
competitive advantage.

00:46:25.100 --> 00:46:30.050
Could the traditional players
be able to acquire those?

00:46:30.050 --> 00:46:30.550
Of course.

00:46:30.550 --> 00:46:31.949
I mean, they have
deep experience

00:46:31.949 --> 00:46:33.740
in building very good
content as you meant.

00:46:33.740 --> 00:46:37.140
They make those
interesting stories.

00:46:37.140 --> 00:46:40.010
They have access to some
of their own platform.

00:46:40.010 --> 00:46:41.690
They can actually
negotiate quite hard.

00:46:41.690 --> 00:46:43.981
I think one other thing that
we didn't have enough time

00:46:43.981 --> 00:46:46.410
to talk about is that a lot
of these online platforms

00:46:46.410 --> 00:46:48.990
actually share no
data with them.

00:46:48.990 --> 00:46:50.365
Some [INAUDIBLE]
because it never

00:46:50.365 --> 00:46:52.114
occurred to them that
they should actually

00:46:52.114 --> 00:46:52.920
ask for that data.

00:46:52.920 --> 00:46:54.940
They don't have the
right sort of skills.

00:46:54.940 --> 00:46:57.610
But I think there is a
possibility that maybe it

00:46:57.610 --> 00:47:00.440
will go in that direction where
these companies will also say,

00:47:00.440 --> 00:47:04.480
I can also use some of these
skills that these forms have

00:47:04.480 --> 00:47:08.050
and build some of that
into my business model.

00:47:08.050 --> 00:47:10.500
So I don't know who is
going to be the winner.

00:47:10.500 --> 00:47:12.610
Maybe there are going
to be some mergers.

00:47:12.610 --> 00:47:13.150
Who knows?

00:47:13.150 --> 00:47:14.750
I mean, that's
really harder to say.

00:47:14.750 --> 00:47:16.750
Maybe Mike can look in
the future better than I.

00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:19.720
MICHAEL SMITH: No, I was going
to say something very similar.

00:47:19.720 --> 00:47:21.520
Going back to "The
Perfect Storm" analogy,

00:47:21.520 --> 00:47:24.599
we all know how the book ends.

00:47:24.599 --> 00:47:25.890
Well, I won't spoil it for you.

00:47:28.950 --> 00:47:32.980
I think we're not saying
that's the preordained outcome

00:47:32.980 --> 00:47:36.060
for the traditional
people in the industry.

00:47:36.060 --> 00:47:39.220
In fact, in Hollywood,
it would be really cool

00:47:39.220 --> 00:47:41.980
if they had an independent
digital distribution

00:47:41.980 --> 00:47:45.999
platform that received funding
from the studios that created--

00:47:45.999 --> 00:47:47.540
and hopefully by
now you've picked up

00:47:47.540 --> 00:47:48.750
that I'm talking about Hulu.

00:47:48.750 --> 00:47:50.181
RAHUL TELANG: Gee.

00:47:50.181 --> 00:47:51.680
MICHAEL SMITH: I
think they actually

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:54.200
have some pretty
interesting assets

00:47:54.200 --> 00:47:56.310
they can bring to bear on this.

00:47:56.310 --> 00:47:57.649
So who wins?

00:47:57.649 --> 00:47:58.190
I don't know.

00:47:58.190 --> 00:48:00.970
But I think this is a
very interesting battle.

00:48:00.970 --> 00:48:05.220
I don't think it's obvious one
side wins and the other side

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:06.370
loses.

00:48:06.370 --> 00:48:08.750
In the end, I think
consumers win.

00:48:08.750 --> 00:48:11.550
And that's the dog
slide at the end.

00:48:11.550 --> 00:48:13.050
AUDIENCE: Just a
follow-up question.

00:48:13.050 --> 00:48:16.430
Have you heard back from
any of your counterparts

00:48:16.430 --> 00:48:19.080
in the industry about what
their reaction to the book is?

00:48:19.080 --> 00:48:21.520
And do they feel threatened?

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:23.900
Do they feel excited about
the changes there are?

00:48:23.900 --> 00:48:25.483
MICHAEL SMITH: Depends
on who you ask.

00:48:25.483 --> 00:48:26.170
RAHUL TELANG: That's right.

00:48:26.170 --> 00:48:28.270
MICHAEL SMITH: I will
say we've presented this

00:48:28.270 --> 00:48:30.340
to three of the six studios.

00:48:30.340 --> 00:48:33.770
And we're presenting
to two more tomorrow.

00:48:33.770 --> 00:48:36.770
And in fact, we've received
really good feedback

00:48:36.770 --> 00:48:41.480
on what we're
saying in the book.

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:44.970
I think they're much more
receptive to this message

00:48:44.970 --> 00:48:48.360
than a lot of people outside
the industry would suspect.

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:50.350
I think the other
thing that we've

00:48:50.350 --> 00:48:52.310
recognized working
with the studios,

00:48:52.310 --> 00:48:55.940
that the studios are not
monolithic in any sense.

00:48:55.940 --> 00:48:58.560
If you ask five people
in a studio what

00:48:58.560 --> 00:49:00.610
they think their digital
strategy ought to be,

00:49:00.610 --> 00:49:04.210
you're going to get
seven different answers.

00:49:04.210 --> 00:49:08.850
There is a strong debate within
the entertainment industry

00:49:08.850 --> 00:49:11.742
today, internally, about
what should we be doing.

00:49:11.742 --> 00:49:13.200
And again, a big
part of the reason

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:14.616
we wanted to write
this book is we

00:49:14.616 --> 00:49:16.600
wanted to give a different
perspective on why

00:49:16.600 --> 00:49:19.632
this is something where
you should move right now.

00:49:19.632 --> 00:49:22.090
RAHUL TELANG: When you get a
speaker from Amazon and Google

00:49:22.090 --> 00:49:24.270
come and talk in the
class in the university,

00:49:24.270 --> 00:49:26.260
every time you hear
is that every decision

00:49:26.260 --> 00:49:28.670
is done made from data.

00:49:28.670 --> 00:49:30.310
No matter how trivial
the decision is,

00:49:30.310 --> 00:49:31.245
we are going to
do an A/B testing.

00:49:31.245 --> 00:49:32.300
We are going to do this.

00:49:32.300 --> 00:49:33.640
We are going to do that.

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:35.150
And then you move
into this world

00:49:35.150 --> 00:49:37.030
where a lot of these
decisions are actually

00:49:37.030 --> 00:49:40.450
not based on serious data.

00:49:40.450 --> 00:49:42.750
It's based on this
is how we did things.

00:49:42.750 --> 00:49:44.830
This is how things work.

00:49:44.830 --> 00:49:47.350
That culture, I think,
probably will change.

00:49:47.350 --> 00:49:50.330
I think increasingly
the firms, they're

00:49:50.330 --> 00:49:52.970
already realizing just hiring
the right sort of talent

00:49:52.970 --> 00:49:58.290
and making sure that the data--
it's a lot of cultural change.

00:49:58.290 --> 00:50:01.404
I'm pretty sure that that
change will take place.

00:50:01.404 --> 00:50:03.320
Well, whether that's
going to be enough or not

00:50:03.320 --> 00:50:05.760
is anybody's guess.

00:50:05.760 --> 00:50:08.060
AUDIENCE: So you
could phrase the thing

00:50:08.060 --> 00:50:10.400
that Rahul was talking
earlier about the distribution

00:50:10.400 --> 00:50:12.880
being a really inefficient
thing, that then we

00:50:12.880 --> 00:50:15.400
had technology that could
overcome that, technology that

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:17.290
could give a better product.

00:50:17.290 --> 00:50:19.010
There's a gap that
existed there.

00:50:19.010 --> 00:50:21.600
There's a gap between what was
possible and what was provided.

00:50:21.600 --> 00:50:23.120
Do you see there's still a gap?

00:50:23.120 --> 00:50:24.790
Have we gotten as
far as we can go?

00:50:24.790 --> 00:50:27.889
Or are there other-- rather
than just-- are we just

00:50:27.889 --> 00:50:29.430
tipping the balance
further from here

00:50:29.430 --> 00:50:31.620
on in of the same kind of stuff?

00:50:31.620 --> 00:50:33.860
Or is there something
different to come?

00:50:33.860 --> 00:50:36.140
Is there still a gap
between what we can do now

00:50:36.140 --> 00:50:37.500
and what is happening?

00:50:37.500 --> 00:50:40.400
RAHUL TELANG: So did you mean
in terms of distribution?

00:50:40.400 --> 00:50:41.700
I wasn't clear.

00:50:41.700 --> 00:50:43.690
AUDIENCE: I was generalizing
from distribution

00:50:43.690 --> 00:50:46.739
in terms of anything
that's possible now.

00:50:46.739 --> 00:50:48.280
Is there still things
that technology

00:50:48.280 --> 00:50:51.530
can do that the movie
industry hasn't leveraged,

00:50:51.530 --> 00:50:52.530
that Netflix doesn't do.

00:50:52.530 --> 00:50:54.820
Netflix has to go into
a new way of dealing

00:50:54.820 --> 00:50:56.244
that it doesn't do yet.

00:50:56.244 --> 00:50:57.910
MICHAEL SMITH: I know
the answer is yes.

00:50:57.910 --> 00:50:59.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:59.240 --> 00:51:00.522
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:51:00.522 --> 00:51:01.480
MICHAEL SMITH: I mean--

00:51:01.480 --> 00:51:02.480
AUDIENCE: Can you see a gap?

00:51:02.480 --> 00:51:03.690
Can you see anything
that you're like,

00:51:03.690 --> 00:51:05.148
oh, I wish they
would fix that or--

00:51:05.148 --> 00:51:08.220
RAHUL TELANG: I feel
like the technology--

00:51:08.220 --> 00:51:11.460
there's one aspect, whether
the technology makes

00:51:11.460 --> 00:51:12.650
a lot of things possible.

00:51:12.650 --> 00:51:14.180
What the challenge
comes is what is

00:51:14.180 --> 00:51:16.200
the business model
behind the technology

00:51:16.200 --> 00:51:17.180
that I can make money?

00:51:17.180 --> 00:51:18.700
I mean, technology
makes it possible

00:51:18.700 --> 00:51:21.470
that I can make the movie
available on streaming

00:51:21.470 --> 00:51:23.150
platform on day one.

00:51:23.150 --> 00:51:24.650
There is enough
bandwidth available.

00:51:24.650 --> 00:51:26.880
There is enough storage
available, all the devices.

00:51:26.880 --> 00:51:28.360
That's possible.

00:51:28.360 --> 00:51:30.960
But there is no
business model that

00:51:30.960 --> 00:51:35.180
will allow the firms to say,
can I profitably do that

00:51:35.180 --> 00:51:39.410
so that I can actually
recover my investment back?

00:51:39.410 --> 00:51:42.420
So the engineers will keep
developing all of these--

00:51:42.420 --> 00:51:45.050
how to distribute better, how
to distribute more efficiently,

00:51:45.050 --> 00:51:46.740
how to lower the
cost of production.

00:51:46.740 --> 00:51:50.011
But then can we have the
business model that allows--

00:51:50.011 --> 00:51:51.760
AUDIENCE: That's kind
of like more faster.

00:51:51.760 --> 00:51:52.930
And that'll keep happening.

00:51:52.930 --> 00:51:53.980
Is that the--

00:51:53.980 --> 00:51:55.440
RAHUL TELANG:
Cheaper and faster.

00:51:55.440 --> 00:51:55.690
AUDIENCE: Cheaper, faster.

00:51:55.690 --> 00:51:57.860
RAHUL TELANG: I think that,
for sure, but as I said,

00:51:57.860 --> 00:52:00.261
what is the business
model on the top of it?

00:52:00.261 --> 00:52:01.760
AUDIENCE: I guess
the transformation

00:52:01.760 --> 00:52:04.940
is that we don't watch the
TV show on the first day it

00:52:04.940 --> 00:52:05.870
comes out anymore.

00:52:05.870 --> 00:52:08.456
I started "House of Cards"
probably four months

00:52:08.456 --> 00:52:11.080
after the first release because
I just didn't get around to it.

00:52:11.080 --> 00:52:13.700
And then I watched
the whole thing.

00:52:13.700 --> 00:52:17.220
That's like a change in
the style of consuming.

00:52:17.220 --> 00:52:18.600
Is there more style changes?

00:52:18.600 --> 00:52:20.680
Or is it just more faster then?

00:52:20.680 --> 00:52:22.180
MICHAEL SMITH: No,
I think there are

00:52:22.180 --> 00:52:25.970
plenty of really interesting
style changes just like that.

00:52:25.970 --> 00:52:28.310
that the audience can
watch it in different ways.

00:52:28.310 --> 00:52:29.770
And that enables
the storytellers

00:52:29.770 --> 00:52:31.936
to tell different stories
that wouldn't have worked.

00:52:31.936 --> 00:52:33.840
And there's this
wonderful feedback loop

00:52:33.840 --> 00:52:36.610
of all sorts of really
cool innovation.

00:52:36.610 --> 00:52:40.660
I think the other thing we're
seeing is a shift from, again,

00:52:40.660 --> 00:52:45.650
when channels are scarce you've
got to have a system that says,

00:52:45.650 --> 00:52:49.520
I'm going to choose what gets
made before it gets made.

00:52:49.520 --> 00:52:52.420
I'm going to have
this choke point.

00:52:52.420 --> 00:52:53.294
It's not arbitrary.

00:52:53.294 --> 00:52:55.710
It's that I can only distribute
a certain amount of stuff.

00:52:55.710 --> 00:52:57.320
So somebody's got to choose.

00:52:57.320 --> 00:52:59.780
One of the wonderful
things about having

00:52:59.780 --> 00:53:01.800
an abundance in
distribution is that you

00:53:01.800 --> 00:53:04.470
can let everything get made
and then on the back end

00:53:04.470 --> 00:53:06.270
see what works.

00:53:06.270 --> 00:53:10.220
My daughter loves watching
videos of other people playing

00:53:10.220 --> 00:53:12.560
Minecraft on YouTube.

00:53:12.560 --> 00:53:17.100
It's not obvious that's
a good idea-- ex-ante.

00:53:17.100 --> 00:53:20.690
But it clearly delivers
a lot of value for her.

00:53:20.690 --> 00:53:21.810
And that's OK.

00:53:21.810 --> 00:53:24.223
As economists we don't judge.

00:53:24.223 --> 00:53:25.306
AUDIENCE: But as a parent.

00:53:25.306 --> 00:53:26.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:27.030 --> 00:53:28.830
MICHAEL SMITH: Fair point.

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:31.590
RAHUL TELANG: He said, who
is going to be the winner?

00:53:31.590 --> 00:53:36.620
I mean, if you look at Netflix,
because of the technology,

00:53:36.620 --> 00:53:39.470
it's easier for them to be
able to offer these shows

00:53:39.470 --> 00:53:40.770
where you can do binge watch.

00:53:40.770 --> 00:53:44.580
On a television, that's
just much harder to do that.

00:53:44.580 --> 00:53:48.160
Now the Netflix of this worlds
are also changing expectations

00:53:48.160 --> 00:53:51.290
from people about what is
the demand in the content?

00:53:51.290 --> 00:53:54.390
Now you ask a 21-year-old
or 18-year-old,

00:53:54.390 --> 00:53:56.120
I mean, for them,
this idea that I'm

00:53:56.120 --> 00:53:58.730
going to watch an
episode from 9:00 to 9:45

00:53:58.730 --> 00:54:01.540
every Thursday, that
just doesn't, I think,

00:54:01.540 --> 00:54:02.990
appeal to them.

00:54:02.990 --> 00:54:05.910
They want it when they want
it at their convenience,

00:54:05.910 --> 00:54:07.160
maybe watch the whole thing.

00:54:07.160 --> 00:54:09.410
And now you can see that
the Netflix platform

00:54:09.410 --> 00:54:10.760
offers that opportunity.

00:54:10.760 --> 00:54:13.550
It gives them that
feature that, again,

00:54:13.550 --> 00:54:16.220
a linear television probably
doesn't give them a feature.

00:54:16.220 --> 00:54:18.000
So if they have to
choose between the two,

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.910
they say, well, then I would
become a Netflix customer

00:54:20.910 --> 00:54:23.970
because Netflix gives me this
tremendous flexibility that I

00:54:23.970 --> 00:54:26.530
can't get on my Comcast
cable connection,

00:54:26.530 --> 00:54:28.420
for example, at least right now.

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:33.026
So I think that's another
element to this competition.

00:54:33.026 --> 00:54:34.026
AUDIENCE: Last question.

00:54:34.026 --> 00:54:34.651
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:54:34.651 --> 00:54:36.885
I guess building on
his thing is, well,

00:54:36.885 --> 00:54:38.510
actually a number of
years ago, my wife

00:54:38.510 --> 00:54:41.059
found this film that was
like audience participation,

00:54:41.059 --> 00:54:42.600
choose your own
adventure thing where

00:54:42.600 --> 00:54:45.350
the audience voted where they
wanted the next scene to go.

00:54:45.350 --> 00:54:47.290
So why aren't
technology companies

00:54:47.290 --> 00:54:49.570
doing that type of thing
with their platforms?

00:54:49.570 --> 00:54:51.620
They seem to have the
ability to do that.

00:54:51.620 --> 00:54:53.695
You're tapped into
everybody's UIs.

00:54:53.695 --> 00:54:55.820
You can say, I want the
next branch to go this way.

00:54:55.820 --> 00:54:57.910
I want the next
branch to go that way.

00:54:57.910 --> 00:54:59.555
AUDIENCE: They're called games.

00:54:59.555 --> 00:54:59.980
RAHUL TELANG: What?

00:54:59.980 --> 00:55:01.271
AUDIENCE: They're called games.

00:55:01.341 --> 00:55:02.840
MICHAEL SMITH: Well,
actually, I was

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:04.131
going in a different direction.

00:55:04.131 --> 00:55:06.360
I was thinking "Epic
Rap Battles of History."

00:55:06.360 --> 00:55:08.630
Have you have you seen this?

00:55:08.630 --> 00:55:10.500
AUDIENCE: Well, you
can vote, like who won.

00:55:10.500 --> 00:55:11.830
MICHAEL SMITH: You can vote.

00:55:11.830 --> 00:55:14.419
AUDIENCE: But you don't, really,
at least from my experience,

00:55:14.419 --> 00:55:16.710
I don't think you chain on
to the next and follow that.

00:55:16.710 --> 00:55:17.100
Or do you?

00:55:17.100 --> 00:55:18.090
MICHAEL SMITH: That's fair.

00:55:18.090 --> 00:55:19.430
That might be the next thing.

00:55:19.430 --> 00:55:20.603
RAHUL TELANG: I forget now.

00:55:20.603 --> 00:55:21.186
It escapes me.

00:55:21.186 --> 00:55:24.530
Wasn't there an ABC
show which actually had

00:55:24.530 --> 00:55:27.217
people can send their
stories and that--

00:55:27.217 --> 00:55:28.050
MICHAEL SMITH: Yeah.

00:55:28.050 --> 00:55:29.758
RAHUL TELANG: And I
think-- I forget it--

00:55:29.758 --> 00:55:32.150
I think it actually
got entangled

00:55:32.150 --> 00:55:34.252
into some sort of
a copyright issue

00:55:34.252 --> 00:55:37.690
where I think the Writers
Association or something said

00:55:37.690 --> 00:55:41.290
you can't really have people
who are not part of the Writers

00:55:41.290 --> 00:55:45.230
Association send the stories
that become part of the net.

00:55:45.230 --> 00:55:47.530
So I'm blanking
on it, but I think

00:55:47.530 --> 00:55:51.750
I had this weird angle to this
whole user-generated content

00:55:51.750 --> 00:55:53.020
going back into the show.

00:55:53.020 --> 00:55:56.840
There was this somewhat
of a bizarre friction.

00:55:56.840 --> 00:55:59.501
And then I think the whole show
then eventually got canceled,

00:55:59.501 --> 00:56:00.000
I believe.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:00.490
I forget.

00:56:00.490 --> 00:56:02.240
MICHAEL SMITH: It was
"In the Motherhood."

00:56:02.240 --> 00:56:03.870
It was this series
a webisodes where

00:56:03.870 --> 00:56:07.050
parents would write in their
most embarrassing child

00:56:07.050 --> 00:56:08.920
stories.

00:56:08.920 --> 00:56:12.320
And then they would create
a webisode around this.

00:56:12.320 --> 00:56:13.680
And I forgot who bought it.

00:56:13.680 --> 00:56:14.620
I think it was ABC--

00:56:14.620 --> 00:56:15.480
RAHUL TELANG: Yeah,
something like that.

00:56:15.480 --> 00:56:16.938
MICHAEL SMITH:
--bought the rights.

00:56:16.938 --> 00:56:19.740
And then as soon as people
started sending in their ideas,

00:56:19.740 --> 00:56:22.570
the Writers Guild came
in and said, that's fine,

00:56:22.570 --> 00:56:25.460
but you've got to pay each
idea that comes in $1,000

00:56:25.460 --> 00:56:29.534
because that's the Guild
minimum for writing.

00:56:29.534 --> 00:56:30.950
So, again, all
that to say there's

00:56:30.950 --> 00:56:32.980
a lot of existing
structures that

00:56:32.980 --> 00:56:35.620
get in the way of innovation.

00:56:35.620 --> 00:56:37.230
But there's also a
whole lot of value

00:56:37.230 --> 00:56:40.840
you could create by doing
some of these innovations.

00:56:40.840 --> 00:56:41.840
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:56:41.840 --> 00:56:42.140
RAHUL TELANG: Thank you.

